<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between PX and REM in CSS?", answer: "PX (pixels) is an absolute unit that stays the same size regardless of user settings. REM (root em) is a relative unit based on the root element's font size (typically 16px by default). Using REM allows your layout to scale when users change their browser's default font size, improving accessibility. If the root font size is 16px, then 1rem equals 16px." },
  { question: "Why should I use REM instead of PX?", answer: "REM units respect user accessibility preferences. When a user increases their browser's default font size for readability, REM-based layouts scale proportionally while PX-based layouts stay fixed. This is especially important for users with low vision. Modern CSS best practice is to use REM for font sizes, padding, and margins, and PX only for borders and fine-detail elements." },
  { question: "What is the default base font size in browsers?", answer: "All major browsers default to a base font size of 16px. This means 1rem equals 16px unless the root font size has been changed. Some developers set the root font size to 62.5% (10px) to make mental math easier: 1.6rem then equals 16px. However, this approach can cause issues with third-party components that assume the standard 16px base." },
  { question: "What is the difference between REM and EM?", answer: "REM is relative to the root element's font size and stays consistent throughout the document. EM is relative to the parent element's font size, which means it compounds when nested. A 2em font inside another 2em container renders at 4x the root size. REM avoids this compounding issue, making it more predictable for layout and typography." },
  { question: "How do I convert PX to REM?", answer: "Divide the pixel value by the base font size. With the default 16px base: 24px / 16 = 1.5rem. For a 10px base (62.5%): 24px / 10 = 2.4rem. This converter handles the math automatically and also shows EM, PT, and percentage equivalents for each pixel value." }
]) %>

